  <h3>Typical Season Rhythm</h3>

  {% set season = state.season or null %}
  {% set spring = season and season.frost and season.frost.spring or null %}
  {% set fall = season and season.frost and season.frost.fall or null %}
  {% set derived = season and season.derived or null %}
  {% set gdd = season and season.gdd and season.gdd.remaining or null %}

  {% set springP50 = spring and spring.p50 or null %}
  {% set fallP50 = fall and fall.p50 or null %}
  {% set frostFreeDays = derived and derived.frostFreeDays_p50 or null %}
  {% set gddAug1 = gdd and gdd["08-01"] or null %}

  {% if not season %}
    <p class="small">Season rhythm guidance isn’t available for this region yet.</p>

  {% elif spring and spring.status == "frost_free" or fall and fall.status == "frost_free" %}
    <p class="small" style="margin-top:-0.25rem;">
      This region is typically frost-free in the normals dataset, so the season is less about a hard frost finish line and more about managing heat, rainfall, and crop maturity over time.
    </p>

  {% else %}
    <p class="small" style="margin-top:-0.25rem;">
      A practical “typical year” rhythm for planning. Use it as a baseline, then adjust for microclimates and variety maturity.
    </p>

    <div class="tableWrap" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">
      <table class="table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Stage</th>
            <th>What it usually means</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Early season</strong></td>
            <td class="small">
              Start cold-tolerant crops, prep beds, and pay more attention to soil warmth and night temperatures than to the calendar alone.
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Main planting</strong></td>
            <td class="small">
              {% if springP50 %}
                Around <strong>{{ springP50 | mmddLong }}</strong>, the main planting push usually begins as frost risk fades.
              {% else %}
                The main planting push usually begins once frost risk starts to ease.
              {% endif %}
              Warm-season crops generally perform best when they get established promptly.
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Peak growth</strong></td>
            <td class="small">
              This is when water, fertility, spacing, and pest pressure have the biggest effect on final yield.
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Late-summer decisions</strong></td>
            <td class="small">
              {% if gddAug1 is not null and gddAug1 >= 800 %}
                There is often enough late-season heat left for a meaningful second round of quick crops.
              {% elif gddAug1 is not null and gddAug1 <= 300 %}
                Late plantings are usually tight, so fast crops and protected spots become much more important.
              {% else %}
                Second plantings can work, but success usually depends on maturity, microclimate, and how warm late summer stays.
              {% endif %}
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Finish window</strong></td>
            <td class="small">
              {% if fallP50 %}
                Plan to have frost-sensitive crops mostly wrapped up by <strong>{{ fallP50 | mmddLong }}</strong>.
              {% else %}
                Plan to have frost-sensitive crops protected or harvested as fall risk increases.
              {% endif %}
              Cooling nights often slow crops before the first real frost arrives.
            </td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    {% if frostFreeDays %}
      <p class="small muted" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">
        Typical season length: <strong>{{ frostFreeDays }}</strong> frost-free days between the median spring and fall frost dates.
      </p>
    {% endif %}
  {% endif %}
</section>